05810nam a22008415i 9781501504914DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97815015049147 a10.1515/97815015049142doi  a(DE-B1597)470421  a(OCoLC)1041993377  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aInternet AccessbAEU 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04aDie babylonisch-assyrische Medizin in Texten und Untersuchungen. nBand 9, pAssyrian and Babylonian Scholarly Text Catalogues ; Medicine, Magic and Divination /cUlrike Steinert. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (VI, 384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDie babylonisch-assyrische Medizin in Texten und Untersuchungen ;vBand 900tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1. Studies on Mesopotamian Text Catalogues -- tOn Three Tablet Inventories -- tA Babylonian Hippocrates -- tTowards a New Perspective on Babylonian Medicine -- tNotes on the Assur Medical Catalogue with Comparison to the Nineveh Medical Encyclopaedia -- tThe Catalogues of Enūma Anu Enlil -- tEsagil-kīn-apli's Catalogue of Sakikkû and Alamdimmû -- tCatalogues, Texts and Specialists -- tPart 2. Text Sources -- t1. The Assur Medical Catalogue (AMC) -- t2. The Exorcist's Manual (KAR 44) -- t3 The Edition of Esagil-kīn-apli's Catalogue of the Series Sakikkû (SA.GIG) and Alamdimmû -- tPlates -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndices0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe reconstruction of ancient Mesopotamian medical, ritual and omen compendia and their complex history is still characterised by many difficulties, debates and gaps due to fragmentary or unpublished evidence. This book offers the first complete edition of the Assur Medical Catalogue, an 8th or 7th century BCE list of therapeutic texts, which forms a core witness for the serialisation of medical compendia in the 1st millennium BCE. The volume presents detailed analyses of this and several other related catalogues of omen series and rituals, constituting the corpora of divination and healing disciplines. The contributions discuss links between catalogues and textual sources, providing new insights into the development of compendia between serialization, standardization and diversity of local traditions. Though its a novel corpus-based approach, this volume revolutionizes the current understanding of Mesopotamian medical texts and the healing disciplines of "conjurer" and "physician". The research presented here allows one to identify core text corpora for these disciplines, as well as areas of exchange and borrowings between them.  afunded by European Research Council (ERC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aAkkadian languagevTexts. 0aAssyro-Babylonian religion. 0aDivinationxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aDivinationzIraq. 0aExorcismxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMagic, Assyro-Babylonian. 0aMedicine, Assyro-Babylonian. 4aMagie. 4aMedizin. 4aMesopotamische Forschung. 4aProphezeiung. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aMedicine.  aMesopotamian scholarship.  adivination.  amagic.1 aSchmidtchen, E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmidtchen, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRochberg, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinkel, Irving L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, J. Cale, econtributor.4ctb4https://